text: Appl Microbiol Biotechnol DOI 10.1007/s00253-015-7248-z Discovery of pentangular polyphenols hexaricins A–C from marine Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 by genome mining Jun Tian 1,2 & Haiyan Chen 2,3,4 & Zhengyan Guo 2 & Ning Liu 2 & Jine Li 2 & Ying Huang 2 & Wensheng Xiang 1 & Yihua Chen 2 Received: 19 October 2015 / Revised: 9 December 2015 / Accepted: 12 December 2015 # Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg 2016 Abstract Many novel microbial nature products were discov- ered from Actinobacteria by genome mining methods. However, only a few number of genome mining works were carried out in rare actinomycetes. An important reason pre- cluding the genome mining efforts in rare actinomycetes is that most of them are recalcitrant to genetic manipulation. H e r e i n , w e c h o s e t h e r a r e m a r i n e a c t i n o m y c e t e Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 to explore its second- ary metabolite diversity by genome mining. The genetic ma- nipulation method has never been established for Streptosporangium strains. At first, we set up the genetic sys- tem of Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 unprecedent- edly. The draft genome sequencing of Streptosporangium sp. Jun Tian and Haiyan Chen contributed equally to this work. Chemistry Technology and Resource Development, Nanning, Guangxi Province 530004, People’s Republic of China School of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering, Guangxi University, Nanning, Guangxi Province 530004, People’s Republic of China xiangwensheng@neau.edu.cn CGMCC 4.7309 revealed that it contains more than 20 cryptic secondary metabolite biosynthetic clusters. A type II polyke- tide synthases-containing cluster (the hex cluster) was predict- ed to encode compounds with a pentangular polyphenol scaf- fold by in silico analysis. The products of the hex cluster were uncovered by comparing the metabolic profile of Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 with that of the hex30 inactivated mutant, in which a key ketoreductase gene was disrupted. Finally, three pentangular polyphenols were isolated and named as hexaricins A (1), B (2), and C (3). The inconsistency of the stereochemistry of C-15 in hexaricins A, B, and C indicates a branch point in their biosynthesis. Finally, the biosynthetic pathway of the hexaricins was pro- posed based on bioinformatics analysis. Keywords Genome mining . Pentangular polyphenol . Polyketide synthase . Streptosporangium . Genetic manipulation Since streptomycin was discovered by Selman Waksman et al., secondary metabolites from actinomycetes have become an important source of small molecule drugs. After around 70 years of screening, more than 10,000 of bioactive small molecules have been isolated from Actinobacteria, including many important antibiotics (erythromycin, vancomycin, and daptomycin), anticancer drugs (bleomycin), and immunosup- pressants (FK506) (Berdy 2005). Surprisingly, the genome sequence data of several Streptomyces strains revealed that even after exhaustive screening, as much as 70 to 90 % of the secondary metabolism potential of the model Actinobacteria remains untapped, let alone the strains not in- tensively studied (Bentley et al. 2002; Ohnishi et al. 2008;

Omura et al. 2001). As more and more actinomycetes genomes are sequenced, it has been convincible that the characterized compounds are merely Bthe tip of the iceberg.^ To explore the chemical diversity embedded inside the Actinobacteria, various genome mining methods have been developed to activate the cryptic secondary metabolite gene clusters and to connect molecules to specific gene clusters (Bachmann et al. 2014; Winter et al. 2011; Zerikly and Challis 2009). Compared to the traditional natural products discovery strat- egies, one advantage of genome mining is that the skeleton or partial structure of the products can be predicted, which is help- ful for choosing appropriate detection methods and for avoiding isolation of known compounds repetitively by in silico de- replication (Boddy 2014; Helfrich et al. 2014). Genome mining efforts in Streptomyces strains were rewarded as plenty of new compounds and some novel chemistries, e.g., in Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2), one of the earliest genome sequenced strains, the natural product families were increased from 4 to 17 after around 10 years of genome mining study (Challis 2014). To date, only limited genome mining works were carried out in rare actinomycetes, by which some compounds with amazing bioactivities were obtained, indicating a high potential of dis- covery of novel structures from those bacteria. For example, the farnesyl dibenzodiazepine, ECO-04601, mined from Micromonospora genome, is now being tested in phase I clinical trials against solid tumor (Farnet Chris et al. 2004).

Streptosporangium is the genus type of the actinobacterial suborder Streptosporangineae, which is named according to its special Bspore-case^ shape. Around 80 compounds have been isolated from the Streptosporangium species, including alka- loids, macrolactams, and aromatic polyketides (Berdy 2005). Two Streptosporangium strains were genome sequenced in- cluding the type strain of this genus S. roseum NI 9100T (ATCC 12428) (Nolan et al. 2010) and S. amethystogenes ASM72107v1 (NRRL B-2639) (Nonomura and Ohara 1960). Analysis of the two genomes revealed that each of them con- tains more than 20 cryptic secondary metabolite biosynthetic gene clusters including polyketides, non-ribosomal peptides, lantipeptides, and terpenes, suggesting Streptosporangium as a fertile natural product source. However, the genome mining and biosynthetic studies have been impeded by the fact that Streptosporangium is unamenable to genetic manipulation. Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 was isolated from the sediment of Lijiao Bay, Huanghai Sea, China (N39°01′ 24.19″; E121°46′03.58″). Analysis of the draft genome se- quence of Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 revealed a cluster containing type II polyketide synthases (PKSs) genes, which may synthesize compounds featuring a hexacyclic skeleton with xanthone structure. A similar cluster was also found in the genome of S. roseum NI 9100T. We established the genetic system of Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 successfully by altering the Escherichia coli- Streptosporangium conjugation conditions carefully. A null

mutant of the type II PKS cluster was then generated by knocking-out a key structure gene. The products of this cluster were searched by fermenting the Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 wild-type strain and the mutant comparably and analyzing their metabolic profiles carefully. Finally, a set of pentangular polyphenols were discovered, and three of them (hexaricins A–C) were isolated and characterized, which have the hexacyclic skeleton as anticipated but do not contain the predicted xanthone moiety. The biosynthetic pathway of the three hexaricins was also proposed. Microorganisms, plasmids, and culture conditions E. coli JM109 was used as a host for plasmid construction, and E. coli ET12567/pUZ8002 was used for E. coli- Streptosporangium conjugation. Both E. coli strains were incu- bated in Luria-Bertani medium at 37 °C. Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 was grown on ISP3 agar at 28 °C for spore preparation. YEME liquid medium was used for Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 genomic DNA isola- tion (Kieser et al. 2000). For production of hexaricins, Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 was cultured in PGG liquid medium (potato starch 1 %, D-glucose 1 %, glycerol 1 %, corn steep liquor 0.25 %, soybean peptone 0.5 %, yeast extract 0.2 %, sea salt 0.1 %, and CaCO3 0.3 %) (Tsurumi et al. 1994). Vector pMD19-T was purchased from Takara (Shiga, Japan); pCIMt002 was used as a suicide vector for gene inactivation in Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 (Li et al. 2015).

PCR reactions were performed with the PrimeSTAR HS DNA polymerase (Takara, Shiga, Japan) or EasyTaq DNA (TransGen Biotech Co., Beijing, China) according to the man- ufacturers’ instructions. The suicide vector for gene inactiva- tion was constructed by ligation-independent cloning strategy (Li and Evans 1997). Genomic DNA isolation of Streptosporangium sp. FXJ7.13 was performed as described (Kieser et al. 2000). The standard protocol for E. coli- Streptomyces conjugations was modified for E. coli- Streptosporangium by omitting the supplemented divalent cations (Kieser et al. 2000). Sequencing and bioinformatics analysis Genomic DNA sequencing was carried out by Majorbio Company (Shanghai, China) using Illumina Hiseq2000 sys- tem. The potential secondary metabolite gene clusters were a n a l y z e d b y a n t i S M A S H ( h t t p : / / a n t i s m a s h . secondarymetabolites.org/) (Blin et al. 2013). The possible Appl Microbiol Biotechnol Appl Microbiol Biotechnol open reading frames were predicted using Prodigal (http:// prodigal.ornl.gov/) (Hyatt et al. 2010). The gene functional annotations were assigned based on the search results of NCBI. Multiple sequence alignment was performed with CLUSTALW (Thompson et al. 1994), and the phylogenetic tree was constructed with MEGA 6.0 using neighbor-joining method (Hall 2013). The bootstrap technique was used to evaluate the tree topology by re-sampling the sequence align- ment 1000 times. The hex gene cluster was deposited in GenBank: KT713752. Inactivation of hex30 in Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309

The 1.4-kb fragment upstream of hex30 (left arm) was PCR cloned with primer pair KR30LF (5′-CTTCCATG GGCACGCCCTAGGGCGCTTGTCAACGGAGAGGC-3′) and KR30LR (5′-ATCCCTTAACGTGAGCCTAGGGCG AACGCGAGCACGGTC-3′) and inserted into the BlnI site of pCIMt002 to generate plasmid pCIMt-KR30L. The 1.5-kb fragment downstream of hex30 (right arm) was then amplified w i t h p r i m e r p a i r K R 3 0 R F ( 5 ′ - C A G T C G AT T GGCTGACAATTGGGTGTCACTCTCAACGTG-3′) and KR30RR (5′-CTTGCTAGCAGATGTCAATTGGTGCGT GTAGACATAGCG-3′) and inserted into the MunI site of pCIMt-KR30L to obtain pCIMt-mKR30. After confirming the fidelity of the PCR-cloned fragments in pCIMt-mKR30 by sequencing, this suicide plasmid was introduced into Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309, and one white colo- ny with apramycin resistance was picked up as the hex30 inactivated mutant CIM-H001, which was confirmed by P C R a n a l y s i s w i t h p r i m e r p a i r K R 3 0 F ( 5 ′ - CATATGACCATCTTCGTCAGGTATCT-3′) and KR30R (5′-GATATCGTAGGTGATGGCAGCAAA-3′) (Fig. 3a, b). Production and isolation of hexaricins A–C

For hexaricin production, Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 spores (∼107 per mL) were inoculated into PGG me- dium at 0.5 % ration (v/v) and cultured at 28 °C, 220 rpm for 7 days.Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 mycelia col- lected from 22L PGG cultures were extracted with acetone. After removing the solvent in vacuo, the dark red materials were re-suspended in 5 L water and extracted with equal vol- ume of CHCl3 for three times. Solvent removal in vacuo was followed by chromatography over a polyamide column (100– 200 mesh, Greenherbs S&T Development Co., Beijing, China) eluted with a gradient of CHCl3–CH3OH. The frac- tions collected was analyzed by TLC and HPLC; and the fractions containing hexaricins were combined, concentrated, and subjected to silica gel chromatography (200–300 mesh, Haiyang Chemical Co., Qingdao, China) and eluted using a gradient of CHCl3–CH3OH. Fractions containing hexaricins were concentrated and refined by semi-preparative HPLC on a ZORBAX StableBond C18 column (5 μm, 250 × 9.4 mm, Agilent, Santa Clara, CA, USA) using CH3OH and water. A gradient elution program was employed as follows: 90–100 % CH3OH (0–22 min), 100 % CH3OH (22–27 min), and 90 % CH3OH (27–30 min); and the three hexaricins were eluted at 7.8 min (hexaricin A), 12.6 min (hexaricin B), and 16.9 min (hexaricin C), respectively. The purified hexaricin A (50 mg), B (6 mg), and C (4 mg) were then characterized by the fol- lowing spectroscopic analyses. Analytical and spectroscopic procedures

HPLC analyses were performed using an Epic C18 column (5 μm, 4.6 × 250 mm, ES Industries, West Berlin, NJ, USA) on Shimadzu HPLC system (Shimadzu, Kyoto, Japan). The column was developed with a linear gradient using CH3OH and water. A gradient elution program was employed as fol- lows: 40–75 % CH3OH (0–10 min), 75–100 % CH3OH (10– 30 min), 100 % CH3OH (30–35 min), and 40 % CH3OH (35– 40 min). The detection wavelength was 450 nm. LC-MS analyses were performed on an Agilent 1260/6460 Triple-Quadrupole LC/MS system (Santa Clara, CA, USA) with an electrospray ionization source. HR-ESI-MS was per- formed on an Agilent 1260 HPLC/6520 QTOF-MS instru- ment (Santa Clara, CA, USA). Optical rotations were mea- sured on the Anton Paar MCP-200 digital automatic polarim- eter (Graz, Austria). CD spectra were recorded on a Chirascan circular dichroism spectrophotometer (Surrey, UK) using methanol as a solvent. NMR analyses were carried out at room temperature on a Bruker-500 NMR spectrometer (Billerica, MA, USA).

Systematic conformational search of hexaricins A–C was carried out by the Conflex 7.0 program with MMFF94 force field (Goto et al. 2013). All of the conformers were further optimized by the B3LYP/6-311G(d,p). The same level harmonic vibrational frequencies were calculated to confirm their stability and to estimate their relative Gibbs free energies at 298.15 K. The electronic circular dichroism (ECD) of hexaricins A and C were calculated using the time-dependent density-functional theory (TD-DFT) method at the PCM/PBE0/6-311++G(d,p) level. The number of sin- glet excited states per conformer was 40. The specific ro- tation of the hexaricins was calculated with the DFT meth- od at the PCM/B3LYP/6-311++G(d,p) level. Solvent effects were considered by the Integral Equation Formalism Polarizable Continuum Model (IEFPCM) in methanol or acetonitrile or chloroform. Finally, the ECDs and the opti- cal rotation of the conformers were Boltzmann weighted according to the calculated Gibbs free energies. The calculated ECD curves were generated using SpecDis1.61 with σ = 0.26 eV and UV shift 10 nm (Bruhn et al. 2013). All DFT calculations were performed using the Gaussian09 program (Frisch et al. 2009).

CGMCC 4.7309

There has been no report about the genetic study on Streptosporangium species. We set out to establish the genetic system of Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 to facilitate our genome mining and the following biosynthetic investiga- tions. After testing different solid media, ISP3 was chosen since it is the only medium that Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 grows and sporulates well. The antibiotic sensitivity test of Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 showed that it is highly sensitive to apramycin, tetracycline, and thiostrepton. In the following studies, 50 μg/mL apramycin has been used for selection. Both protoplast trans- formation and E. coli-Streptosporangium conjugation were tested to establish the genetic system of Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309, and neither of them worked at the stan- dard conditions. For the former method, we were stuck in preparing high-quality protoplasts; for the later one, we ob- served that the strain grew poorly when Mg2+ or Ca2+ was supplemented, which was usually added in solid medium to increase the exconjugant frequency between E. coli and Streptomyces (Flett et al. 1997). Finally, the E. coli- Streptosporangium conjugation method was established by using ISP3 agar plate without divalent metal ion supplemen- tation, and the exconjugant frequencies for nonreplicating plasmids such as pSET152 were about 10−6 to 10−7. Genome sequencing and analysis of type II PKSs containing cluster

The Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 genome was draft sequenced using Illumina Hiseq2000 system. Analysis of the genome by antiSMASH revealed more than 20 cryptic secondary metabolite biosynthetic gene clusters including two clusters containing type II PKSs. In this study, we focused on one of the type II PKSs clusters (named the hex cluster), which contains 33 open reading frames including genes encoding the minimal PKS units ketosynthase α (KSα, Hex24), KSβ (Hex23), and acyl carrier protein (Hex22) (Fig. 1, Table 1). Type II PKSs cluster sharing high similarities in both gene orga- nization and protein sequences with the hex cluster was also found in the genome of S. roseum NI 9100T (Table 1). The minimal PKS is responsible for synthesizing a polyke- tide intermediate, which is further cyclized, aromatized, and modified by various tailoring enzymes to afford the final aro- matic products. Among the three components of the minimal PKS, KSβ is the determinant of the polyketide chain length and has been used as a robust phylogenetic marker to predict

the architecture of type II PKS products (Kang and Brady 2014). Hex24 and Hex23 show high similarities with KSα and KSβ units involved in pentangular polyphenol biosynthe- sis (e.g., 75 and 65 % identities to XanF and XanE from xantholipin biosynthesis, respectively) (Zhang et al. 2012), indicating that the products of the hex cluster are also pentangular polyphenols. A phylogenetic inspection of Hex23 together with KSβ units from the other pentangular polyphenol clusters revealed that Hex23 fell into the subclade of pentangular polyphenols with a 26-carbon skeleton (Fig. 2). Most of the hex genes encoding proteins share high similari- ties with enzymes involved in the biosynthesis of xantholipin (Zhang et al. 2012) and lysolipin (Lopez et al. 2010) (Table 1), both of which are pentangular polyphenols with featured xan- thone moieties. Moreover, Hex18 displays 69 % identity with XanO4 (Zhang et al. 2012), the proposed Baeyer-Villiger monooxygenase involved in xanthone moiety formation and the active site residues conserved in this family of monooxygenases were also found in Hex18 (Fig. S1), indicat- ing that hexaricins also have the xanthone moiety. Therefore, we predicted the hex cluster dictates hexacyclic pentangular polyphenols with a core structure depicted in Fig. 2b, which has a 26-carbon xanthone skeleton as xantholipin.

There are only four reported pentangular polyphenols iso- lated from the Streptosporangium species including angucuclinone R2 from Streptosporangium sp. Sg3 (Boudjella et al. 2010) and WS79089A, WS79089B, and WS79089C from S. roseum No. 79089 (Tsurumi et al. 1994) (Fig. 2c), which are obviously different to the predicted struc- ture in Fig. 1a, implying a good chance to discover new struc- ture of pentangular polyphenols from Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309. Hex30 is a putative ketoreductase showing 62 % identity to LlpZIII, which was proposed to catalyze the ketoreduction at C-6 in lysolipin I biosynthesis (Lopez et al. 2010). C-6 ketoreduction normally happens before the first polyketide ring cyclization, which is at the very early stage of polyketide biosynthesis, and the final aromatic products should be totally abolished in the C-6 ketoreduction null mutant (Javidpour et al. 2013). To uncover the products of the hex cluster, the Δhex30 mutant CIM-H001 was constructed by replacing hex30 with the apramycin resistance cassette aac(3)IV (Fig. 3a) and validated by PCR analysis (Fig. 3b). CIM- H001 was then used as a negative control and fermented com- parably with Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 in vari- ous liquid media. All pentangular polyphenols are colorful due to the large conjugated system in their structures, which facilitates the mining process significantly by directly compar- ing the colors of CIM-H001 and Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 cultures. When growing in the PGG medium, Fig. 1 The organization of the hexaricin biosynthetic gene cluster. Proposed functions for individual open reading frames are shown in Table 1

we noticed that Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 pro- duced a group of red compounds, which were absent in the CIM-H001 culture. HPLC analyses revealed several peaks possessing similar UV spectra (with a featured absorbance around 475 nm) appearing only in the Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 cell extract (Fig. 3c). We proposed those peaks represented the hexacyclic polyphenols produced by the hex cluster and termed them hexaricins. exists in this compound. To confirm the structure of hexaricin A, we analyzed its 2D NMR (COSY, HSQC, and HMBC) data (Fig. S2E-G) carefully and determined undoubtedly that it share a same planar structure with WS79089A. There are two stereogenic carbon centers inside hexaricin A, indicating that four potential stereoisomers exist. The circular dichroism (CD) spectrum of hexaricin A matched well with the theoret- ical calculated ECD spectrum of the (11R, 15R) stereoisomer (Fig. S3). The theoretical specific rotation data of hexaricin A a 600 MHz b 150 MHz c 500 MHz d 125 MHz were also calculated and tested (Table S1), which also sup- ported the absolute configuration of hexaricin A is (11R, 15R). Hexaricin B is also a scarlet powder. Its molecular formula was determined to be C29H22O10 by ESI-MS (m/z 531.1 [M + H]+) and HR-ESI-MS (m/z 529.1132 [M − H]−, calculated 529.1135) (Fig. S4A-B), the same as that of WS79089C. The 1H NMR data of hexaricin B (Table 2, Fig. S4C) are almost identical to WS79089C, suggesting the two com- pounds have the same planar structure. Genome sequencing reveals that Streptosporangium has con- siderable potential in synthesizing secondary metabolites. However, the lack of genetic manipulation method precludes the genome mining attempts to explore the metabolite diver- sities of this species. In the present work, we set up the genetic system of Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 and inactivated a ketoreductase gene of the hex cluster, which is the first reported genetic manipulation in Streptosporangium. Three pentangular polyphenols, hexaricins A–C, were then mined from Streptosporangium sp. CGMCC 4.7309 with the aid of in silico prediction and metabolic profile compari- son. The discovery of hexaricins revealed the advantages and limitations of in silico prediction in genome mining work representatively. On one hand, the products of the hex cluster were predicted to be colorful pentangular polyphenols, which simplified our product searching process significantly by only Fig. 5 The proposed biosynthetic pathway of hexaricins. checking the cultures’ colors, exemplifying the power of in silico prediction. On the other hand, the discrepancy between the predicted xantholipin-like scaffold (Fig. 2b) and the struc- tures of hexaricins represents the limitation of in silico meth- od. The xantholipin-like scaffold in Fig. 2b was predicted based on the homologies between hexaricin and xantholipin biosynthetic enzymes, especially XanO4 (69 % identity to Hex18), which was proposed to be responsible for xanthone moiety formation. In addition, the hex cluster also contains an asparagine synthase-like protein encoding gene (hex6) as the xantholipin gene cluster (xanA). Hex6 displays 53 % identity to XanA and 52 % identity to FdmV from fredericamycin biosynthetic gene cluster. The latter one was characterized to be an amide synthetase catalyzing the formation of the lactam ring F (Chen et al. 2010). The active site residues essential to FdmV were all conserved in Hex6 (Fig. S8), supporting the predicted scaffold in Fig. 2b containing a lactam ring F moi- ety. Surprisingly, neither xanthone moiety nor lactam ring F exists in hexaricins, reminding us the limitation of in silico analysis. One plausible explanation about the discrepancy be- tween the predicted and the characterized structures is that although genes like hex6 and hex18 are present in the hex cluster, they might be transcriptional deficiency at the specific fermentation condition for hexaricin production. Further transcriptomic or proteomic analysis of all the hex genes should be helpful to find the reason causing this inconsistence. Among the three pentangular polyphenols, hexaricins A and B have the same planar structures as WS79089A and WS79089C, respectively. hexaricins A and B are both 11R, 15R, while the absolute configurations of WS79089A and WS79089C have never been studied. Hexaricin C is a novel structure compound lack- ing the 11-OH group when compared with hexaricin A; and, surprisingly, it has a 15S configuration, which implies a branch point in hexaricins’ biosynthetic pathway. As WS79089A and WS79089C, hexaricins possess no clear an- tibiotic activity against either gram-positive (Bacillus subtilis) or gram-negative (E. coli) bacteria (data not shown). Considerably, both WS79089A and WS79089C are highly selective endothelin-converting enzyme inhibitors. The endothelin-converting enzyme inhibition activity of hexaricins A–C will be tested in the following studies (Tsurumi et al. 1994).

A biosynthetic pathway of hexaricins was proposed based on analyses of the hex cluster and the structures of hexaricins A–C (Fig. 5). At first, a tridecaketide chain is synthesized by the minimal PKS (Hex22, Hex23, and Hex24). The cycliza- tion and aromatization steps catalyzed by Hex21, Hex25, and Hex26 should take place after the 6-ketoreduction catalyzed by Hex30 to form the pentangular skeleton. The 11- ketoreduction was proposed to be catalyzed by Hex19, which displays 55 % identity with BenL, the ketoreductase respon- sible for 11-ketoreduction in benastatin biosynthesis (Xu et al. 2007). We proposed that Hex20 and Hex33 catalyze the hy- droxylations at C-3 and C-4 respectively, and the resulted hydroquinone ring B will oxidized spontaneously to form the quinone moiety according to a similar oxidation process in fredericamycin biosynthesis catalyzed by FdmM1 (38 % identity to Hex20) and FdmM (46 % identity to Hex33) (Chen et al. 2009). The 10-O-methylation step was suggested to be catalyzed by O-methyltransferase Hex7 or Hex9. Most of the F rings in pentangular polyphenols are aromatized. Specially, hexaricins have a saturated bond between C-14 and C-15; and the absolute configuration of C-15 is different in hexaricin A (15R), B (15R), and C (15S), indicating a new strategy to diversify pentangular polyphenol structures. The saturated bond between C-14 and C-15 and the different ste- reoisomers might be introduced by a ketoreductase (Hex29) and a dehydration step. The resulted 15R-stereoisomer, hexaricin A, is decorated by an acetyltransferase to generate hexaricin B; while the 15S-stereoisomer is modified by the following dehydration and enol reduction steps to form hexaricin C. Considering that several other hex genes encoding putative tailoring enzymes are not involved in the biosynthesis of hexaricins A–C (e.g., hex6 and hex18), the three hexaricins might be further decorated by those tailoring enzymes to generate novel analogs at certain conditions, which is an interesting point deserving further studies.
